<subSubSection id="1D98654B6001FF8876AAF9ABBAC444F3" pageId="5" pageNumber="562" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="553D36C06001FF8876AAF9ABBAC444F3" blockId="5.[151,1436,1577,1818]" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">
<emphasis id="67F6EAD26001FF8876AAF9ABB829443B" bold="true" box="[151,273,1577,1602]" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Members of this subgenus may usually be recognized by the presence of supernumerary crossveins in both the clavus and corium of the forewing, the relatively long, slender aedeagus, and the medial posterior lobe of female abdominal sternite VII either absent or no wider than the lateral lobes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1D98654B6001FF8876FAF917BC724563" pageId="5" pageNumber="562" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="553D36C06001FF8876FAF917BC724563" blockId="5.[151,1436,1577,1818]" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">
<emphasis id="67F6EAD26001FF8876FAF917B80344D7" bold="true" box="[199,315,1685,1710]" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">Remarks.</emphasis>
This subgenus is less well defined and more morphologically heterogeneous than 
<taxonomicName id="92824D436001FF88730CF917BB7344A8" authority="Sinada &amp; Blocker. Most" authorityName="Sinada &amp; Blocker. Most" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Polyamia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="562" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Copolyamia">
<emphasis id="67F6EAD26001FF88730CF917BCA444D4" box="[1329,1436,1685,1709]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">Polyamia</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="67F6EAD26001FF88769DF938B81144AB" box="[160,297,1722,1746]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">Copolyamia</emphasis>
) Sinada &amp; Blocker. Most
</taxonomicName>
species occur in subtropical and tropical grasslands of 
<collectingRegion id="9746F8226001FF887281F93BBC2A44AB" box="[1212,1298,1721,1746]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">
<collectingCountry id="2D9576506001FF887281F93BBC2A44AB" box="[1212,1298,1721,1746]" name="Mexico" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">Mexico</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
and Central America, although the 
<typeStatus id="8A3988626001FF88779DF95CB8E8448F" box="[416,464,1758,1782]" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">type</typeStatus>
species, 
<taxonomicName id="92824D436001FF887401F95CBA6E448C" authority="Van Duzee" authorityName="Van Duzee" authorityYear="1892" box="[572,854,1757,1782]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Deltocephalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="562" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="weedi" subGenus="Polyamia">
<emphasis id="67F6EAD26001FF887401F95CBB72448C" box="[572,586,1758,1781]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">P</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis id="67F6EAD26001FF887459F95CBB4A448C" box="[612,626,1758,1781]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">P</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis id="67F6EAD26001FF8874B1F95FBBF5448C" box="[652,717,1757,1781]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">weedi</emphasis>
Van Duzee
</taxonomicName>
, illustrated below (
<figureCitation id="CDB92A456001FF887208F95FBDA5448F" box="[1077,1181,1757,1782]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 7" captionStart-1="FIGURE 8" captionStartId-0="8.[151,250,869,891]" captionStartId-1="8.[151,250,1938,1960]" captionTargetBox-0="[171,1416,203,838]" captionTargetBox-1="[191,1375,949,1909]" captionTargetId-0="figure@8.[151,1436,193,848]" captionTargetId-1="figure@8.[169,1396,925,1926]" captionTargetPageId-0="8" captionTargetPageId-1="8" captionText-0="FIGURE 7. Polyamia (Polyamia) weedi A–B: habitus, dorsal view; C: habitus, lateral view; D: face." captionText-1="FIGURE 8. Polyamia (Polyamia) weedi A: male pygofer lobe, lateral view; B: male pygofer and segments X–XI, dorsal view; C: valve, subgenital plates and styles, ventral view; D: style, dorsal view; E, F: connective and aedeagus, dorsal and lateral view, respectively." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/1458055/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/1458057/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">Figs 7–8</figureCitation>
), is widespread in the eastern 
<collectingCountry id="2D9576506001FF8876D0F880B8114563" box="[237,297,1794,1818]" name="United States of America" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">USA</collectingCountry>
. Here we describe the first species of the subgenus (and genus) recorded from South America.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
